benchmark_config.jira_title: Implement/Test API: PUT /1.0/kb/accounts/{accountId}/paymentMethods/{paymentMethodId}/setDefault - Set the default payment method

covered: Valid PUT request scenarios covered (TC01, TC02, TC03, TC04, TC05) with 204 responses and default-set behavior.
Non-Existing Resource scenarios covered (TC08, TC09, TC10) with 404 errors and appropriate messages.
Authorization and header handling covered (TC11 missing header, TC12 unauthorized).
Input validation and boundary checks covered (TC06 invalid accountId format, TC07 invalid paymentMethodId format, TC16 min/max UUID, TC23 partial UUIDs).
Error handling and service unavailability covered (TC13 503, TC18 504/503 depending on timeout).
Injection and security checks covered (TC19 header injection).
PayAllUnpaidInvoices flow covered (TC02 with true, TC05 with no unpaid invoices, TC17 performance scenario).
Regression tests covered (TC20 clearing old default, TC21 account with no payment methods).
Concurrency and performance coverage (TC22 concurrent updates; TC17 large unpaid invoices).
Boundary and existence checks for UUIDs (TC16) and account/paymentMethod belonging checks (TC10).
gaps: Pagination: PUT endpoint does not return a list; pagination testing is not applicable for this resource.
Rate Limiting: no tests covering throttling or rate limits for concurrent PUTs.
Caching Behavior: no tests validating caching headers (ETag, Cache-Control).
Partial Update: PUT semantics focused on default-set; explicit partial-update tests are not applicable but worth clarifying in design/docs.
Internal server error (500) scenarios not explicitly tested beyond 503/504 behavior.
Additional invalid header values and malformed payload scenarios could be expanded (e.g., malformed query strings, invalid pluginProperty shapes).
recommendations: Add explicit rate-limiting and caching-header tests for the PUT /setDefault flow.
Introduce a dedicated 500 Internal Server Error test to validate server fault handling beyond 503/504.
Expand header validation coverage with more invalid/edge header values and malformed inputs.
Document and test behavior for edge-case payloads or future payloads (if API evolves to accept a body for this operation).
Enhance concurrency testing with heavier load profiles and longer-running stress scenarios beyond TC22.
